(43, 4, 44, 41, 6, 4, 4, 'a prophet hath no honour in his own country', 'Honor of a Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of honor a prophet receives in his own country. This connection highlights a shared theme regarding the reception of prophets among their own people.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 45, 43, 2, 23, 23, NULL, 'Connection of Belief and Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the response of belief in Jesus due to the miracles he performed. In John 2:23, many believed in his name after seeing the miracles in Jerusalem, which is echoed in John 4:45, where the Galileans received him after witnessing his works at the feast.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 45, 43, 2, 13, 16, 'having seen all the things that he did', 'Jesus'' Reception in Galilee', 'This connection highlights the Galileans'' response to Jesus after witnessing his actions in Jerusalem. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' actions at the feast, which influenced the Galileans'' reception of him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 45, 5, 16, 16, 16, 'having seen all the things that he did', 'Connection of Feasts and Reception', 'This connection highlights the importance of feasts in both passages. In John 4:45, the Galileans'' reception of Jesus is linked to their participation in the feast, paralleling Deuteronomy 16:16''s mandate for males to appear before the Lord at feasts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 45, 42, 9, 53, 53, 'received him', 'Reception of Jesus in Galilee', 'This connection highlights the contrasting receptions of Jesus in Galilee and Samaria. While the Galileans received him after witnessing his miracles, the Samaritans did not receive him due to his intention to go to Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 45, 40, 4, 23, 24, 'the Galileans received him', 'Connection of Jesus'' Healing Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the reception of Jesus in Galilee and his healing activities. John highlights the Galileans'' recognition of Jesus'' earlier works, which sets the stage for his subsequent ministry described in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 45, 42, 2, 42, 44, 'went unto the feast', 'Connection of Jesus'' Presence in Feasts', 'This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' presence at religious feasts. Both passages emphasize the importance of going to Jerusalem for the feast, showcasing a continuity in Jesus'' life and ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 43, 2, 1, 11, 'Cana of Galilee', 'Miracles in Cana of Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' presence in Cana of Galilee, where he performs significant miracles. The first passage introduces a nobleman seeking healing for his son, while the second recounts Jesus'' first miracle of turning water into wine, showcasing his divine authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 19, 50, 15, 15, NULL, 'Deliverance in Times of Trouble', 'This connection highlights the theme of calling upon Jesus in times of distress, as seen in both passages. The nobleman seeks Jesus for healing his sick son, paralleling the call for deliverance in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 28, 5, 15, 15, 'sick at Capernaum', 'Seeking Help in Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize seeking help in times of distress. In John, the nobleman seeks Jesus for healing, paralleling Hosea''s call for seeking God in affliction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 40, 9, 18, 18, NULL, 'Healing of the Sick', 'Both passages emphasize the desperation of parents seeking healing for their children. The nobleman in John seeks help for his sick son, while the ruler in Matthew seeks Jesus to revive his dead daughter.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 40, 15, 22, 22, 'son was sick', 'Healing and Mercy Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the need for healing and mercy. The nobleman seeks help for his sick son, while the Canaanite woman pleads for her daughter, who is afflicted. This connection highlights the compassionate response of Jesus to those in distress.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 42, 7, 2, 2, 'sick', 'Sick Servants in Need', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a nobleman and a centurion seeking help for their sick servants. This connection highlights the urgency and desperation of both figures as they turn to Jesus for healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 46, 42, 8, 42, 42, NULL, 'Healing of Dying Children', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of healing for children. In John, a nobleman''s son is sick, while in Luke, a father seeks help for his dying daughter.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 43, 4, 3, 3, NULL, 'Journey from Judea to Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement from Judea into Galilee. This journey sets the stage for the healing of the official''s son, highlighting the significance of Jesus'' presence in Galilee.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 41, 2, 1, 3, 'heal his son', 'Healing of the Sick', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking Jesus for healing. In John, a father pleads for his dying son, while in Mark, friends bring a paralyzed man to Jesus. This connection highlights the theme of faith in Jesus'' healing power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 41, 6, 55, 56, 'besought him that he would come down', 'Healing and Faith in Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking Jesus for healing. In John, the official begs Jesus to heal his son, while in Mark, people bring the sick to Jesus, hoping for healing by touching him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 42, 7, 6, 8, NULL, 'Authority and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of authority in healing. In John, the nobleman seeks Jesus'' intervention for his dying son, while in Luke, the centurion expresses faith in Jesus'' authority to heal without physical presence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 42, 8, 41, 41, 'besought him that he would come', 'Healing Requests to Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals seeking Jesus for healing. Both passages feature men who beseech Jesus to come and heal their loved ones, emphasizing their desperation and faith in His ability to heal.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 43, 4, 54, 54, 'come out of Judea into Galilee', 'Miracles in Galilee', 'This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' miracles in Galilee, specifically referencing the healing of the official''s son. Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement from Judea to Galilee, marking a pivotal moment in his ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 47, 44, 9, 38, 38, 'besought him that he would come down', 'Seeking Healing from Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking help from a leader for healing. In John, the man seeks Jesus to heal his son, while in Acts, the disciples seek Peter to help a deceased woman. This connection highlights the reliance on spiritual leaders for miraculous interventions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 43, 20, 29, 29, 'Except ye see signs and wonders', 'Belief and Seeing in John', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief based on sight. In both passages, Jesus addresses the necessity of seeing signs to believe, contrasting it with the blessing of those who believe without seeing.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 46, 1, 22, 22, 'Except ye see signs and wonders', 'Signs and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of signs for belief. In John, Jesus points out that people will not believe without seeing signs, while in 1 Corinthians, it is stated that the Jews require a sign to validate their faith.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 58, 2, 4, 4, 'signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of signs and wonders in belief. John 4:48 highlights the necessity of witnessing these miracles for faith, while Hebrews 2:4 describes God bearing witness through signs and wonders.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 27, 4, 2, 2, 'signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''signs and wonders'' in belief and testimony. John 4:48 highlights the necessity of witnessing miracles for faith, while Daniel 4:2 reflects on the signs and wonders performed by God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 43, 12, 37, 37, 'signs and wonders', 'Connection of Belief and Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in relation to miracles. In both passages, the emphasis is on the necessity of signs and wonders for belief, with John 4:48 stating, ''Except ye see signs and wonders, ye will not believe,'' and John 12:37 noting that despite many miracles, they ''believed not on him.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 44, 2, 22, 22, 'signs and wonders', 'Connection of Signs and Wonders', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of signs and wonders in belief. John 4:48 highlights the necessity of witnessing such acts for faith, while Acts 2:22 references Jesus'' miracles as proof of his divine approval.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 48, 40, 24, 24, 24, 'signs and wonders', 'Connection of Signs and Wonders', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of signs and wonders in relation to belief. John 4:48 warns that belief often hinges on witnessing such phenomena, while Matthew 24:24 cautions that false prophets will also perform great signs and wonders, potentially deceiving believers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
